I think this is a typo in wrapping `curio.ssl.get_server_socket`, instead of 

    @wraps(_ssl.wrap_socket)

, it should be

    @wraps(_ssl.get_server_certificate)

Given a Yang file like this:

    module a {
      namespace "urn:a";
      prefix a;

      container a {
        leaf b {
          type union {
            type uint32 {
              range "1..2000000000";
            }
            type enumeration {
              enum "max"                          { value -1; }
            }
          }
          default "max";
        }
      }
    }

The method pyang.types.IntStypeSpec.validate will be called with "max" as the val argument, which will kind of work with Python 2 because comparing strings and integers is allowed, but it will raise a TypeError with Python 3.

This validation should not be tried in the first place as "max" is not a possible default for an integer.
A quick fix would be to add a check for 'min' and 'max' at the beginning of validate, but it seems to me that a better way to fix it would be to remove 'min' and 'max' from the str_to_val method because 'min' and 'max' are only valid within the range and length statements.

It also applies to Decimal64.

