I'm building a small proof-of-concept but am having issues getting dependencies to work correctly. In the example below, the PrintNumbers task runs and prints the numbers 1 to 10. After that, I'd expect that the PrintMoreNumbers task would then start and do the same thing. However, what actually happens is the PrintNumbers task starts again. Could someone assist in pointing out what I am overlooking?

``` python
class PrintNumbers(luigi.Task):
    def run(self):
        for i in range(1, 10):
            print("PrintNumbers" + str(i))
            time.sleep(1)
        print("PrintNumbers Completed.")


class PrintMoreNumbers(luigi.Task):
    def requires(self):
        return(PrintNumbers())
    def run(self):
        for i in range(1, 10):
            print("PrintMoreNumbers" + str(i))
            time.sleep(1)
        print("PrintMoreNumbers Completed.")


if __name__ == '__main__':

    luigi.run(['PrintMoreNumbers'])
```

